subject: Support for configurable host reboot count
commitMessage:
Support for configurable host reboot count

Changed so that the AsyncResp object can read the amount of reboot
"AttemptsLeft" from the dbus property hosted by state manager.
As supposed to the hard coded "3",which was a static value based off
the BOOT_COUNT_MAX_ALLOWED definition.

Tested:
   - tests built and passed with docker.
   - failing redfish validator testing.(TODO)

curl -k -H "X-AUTH" -X GET https://${BMC_IP}/redfish/v1/Systems/system/

"Boot": {
    "AutomaticRetryAttempts": 3,
    "AutomaticRetryConfig": "RetryAttempts",
    "AutomaticRetryConfig@Redfish.AllowableValues": [
      "Disabled",
      "RetryAttempts"
    ],

Signed-off-by: Corey Hardesty <corey.hardesty@icloud.com>
Change-Id: I034782847a2318e2604bdd0cf33cdf705d224acb

Please do not hardcode subtree index here, nobody can make sure subtree[2] is what you really want.

I was told to use the mapper. So I can do two things.
1. I can just hard code the paths for this getProperty(attempt paths)
2. I can parse the subtree for the correct service/path.
Which would you prefer I do?

My suggestion is separating getting RebootPolicy/RebootAttempts into two functions, and hardcode using subtree[0] like getTrustedModuleRequiredToBoot() in the same file does. The 3rd parameter of GetSubTree (interfaces) is an OR condition, and dbus object containg either 1 of the 2 interfaces. In this case, subtree[0] may not always the one have the Policy interface, same applies to subtree[2].

Since you are only going to add getting RebootAttempts in this patch, I think you only need to add the function to get it with mapper. No need to touch the exising RebootPolicy.

I'm thinking I will restore this function back to the original,and modify it to retrieve AttemptsLeft/RetryAttempts in a seperate function call if autoreboot is enabled. This will allow the hardcoding of subtree[0] since they are hosted by the same service/path.
My original concern was altering the behavior of the original implementation, but since "autoreboot" may be disabled it doesn't really matter if the value of RetryAttempts is reported.
